node.text:
Tomorrow morning YOU can experience the excitement & adrenaline of conservation work at home...(link in bio to join in 🙌)
My good buddy Dr. Joel @the_conservation_vet is working with the @blueskysociety to collar African elephants in the greater Kruger area and if you purchase tickets to see this process live you’re actually making a donation to help out wild elephants 😁. Collaring Wild elephants requires helicopters, intensive veterinary care, and lots of feet on the ground AKA it’s pretty expensive. The real value in collaring comes from the scientific, ecologically significant research to follow, helping prevent human:wildlife conflict (which is massively important regarding elephants), and influencing policy to better protect our wildlife & habitats. 
I put a link in my bio if you’d like to see this crazy process from home and help the elephants in doing so. 
And give Dr. Joel ( @the_conservation_vet ) here a “happy birthday” for me tomorrow because this guy is collaring elephants on his birthday 🥳🔥❗️
#elephant #wildlife #conservation #research #humanwildlifeconflict #policy #🌍 #🇿🇦

node.text:
Did you know dogs can tear their ACLs too❓In dogs it’s actually called a “CrCL” (Cranial Cruciate Ligament), anatomically identical to people’s anterior cruciate ligaments, and one of the most common orthopedic injuries in dogs. 
You’re looking at a positive “cranial drawer sign” and this orthopedic exam finding is highly indicative of CrCL damage specifically. A recent history of acute onset unilateral non-weight bearing to weight bearing pelvic limb lameness (aka sudden limping on back leg that was worst initially but improving a little) also supports this diagnosis. Radiographic evidence (aka “x-rays”) of stifle effusion (aka fluid in the knee joint space) can also indicate ligament damage. 
Did you know that when a dog ruptures their CrCL they have >50% chance of rupturing the other leg’s CrCL in their life❓(Most commonly within 2 years). 
Surgery is highly recommended in most cases but rather than replacing/repairing the damaged ligament with a graft or donor ligament veterinarians instead stabilize the joint by modifying the tibia (aka main lower leg bone) just under the stifle (aka knee joint) to change the mechanics of how the femur (upper leg bone) & tibia interact during activity. 
Surgery requires a post operative rehab period of ~12 weeks but the short term and long term benefits are significant. Stabilizing the injured stifle significantly reduces osteoarthritis over the patient’s lifetime. For dogs with old CrCL injuries - surgical stabilization often benefits them too. 
@conejovet

Yo❗️ @printsforwildlife is back‼️ 
This is such a unique campaign that was launched last year as a way to raise critically needed funding for conservation and communities during covid through a 30-day print sale of some of the best wildlife photography that exists! Last year they raised $660K for @africanparksnetwork – a conservation organization that manages 19 parks in 11 countries across Africa for wildlife and people. This year, Prints for Wildlife is back with over 170 globally renowned wildlife photographers who are donating an epic image – where only 100 copies of each are available for just $100. 100% of proceeds after printing and handling goes back once again to African Parks. Images are selling out, and there’s only two more weeks of the sale (which will run to August 11th). Go to @printsforwildlife where 10 new images have been released just today; there are over 190 to choose from now, and it’s for a limited time and a great cause. Click the link in my bio to go directly to the store (link: www.printsforwildlife.org). 
#wildlife #conservation

Zou zike ze Z chairs⁉️
These were my first furniture project since starting hobbyist woodworking last year. 
I’ve fell in love with woodworking because it combines my mathematic/engineering brain with the ability to exercise creative artistry and, if things go as planned, the end result is very rewarding 🪵🪚🤓!
I made a short video (swipe) explaining the early design stages because I pretty much had to build from scratch - not easy, but def makes me even more proud of them 🙈. 
-🪵: kiln dried domestic walnut 
-Finish: dark walnut stain followed by de-waxed shellac (sanding sealer) followed by oil-base polyurethane semigloss. 
#vooderinarian

Did you know many parrot species have exceptional & unique personalities? Parrots can contribute to the human:animal bond every bit as much as dogs or cats 🐣🤗. 
DISCLAIMER: I do NOT recommend most parrots species for most people. Many of these beautiful birds have very specific nutritional, habitat, and EMOTIONAL needs that only a handful of parrot-parents can accommodate to. Even a little conure like this needs to receive a lot of attention every single day. Cockatiels are probably, all-around, the best option for a parrot pet and they can be very happy in captivity. Common mistakes people make is taking home an African grey parrot or a macaw or a cockatoo - these birds can be very loud (esp macaws & cockatoos) and unfortunately, many of them are relinquished to avian rescues because their previous owners weren’t prepared for a pet like this and changed their mind 😔. That being said - if you’re looking for a flying friend then please find out if there’s a parrot/bird rescue in your local area! Just like dog & cat rescues (and rabbit, guinea pig, reptile etc) there’s a lot of great birds that need homes. 
And whether you’re looking to adopt or purchase a parrot PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE do your research‼️🙏 I say this for any pet species because they each have specific requirements including nutritional needs, space, enrichment, temperature, UVB light, humidity, cuddle time (or not), intra-species social opportunity (i.e. social animals like guinea pigs & rabbits should always have a like-species friend), and of course pet parent patience (in the case of a macaw screaming so loud an entire jungle can hear it at 6am every single day)! If you can’t provide the right life for these animals then they’re not the ideal pet for you. And trust me on that. I see this constantly as an exotic animal vet - people bring in pets for problems that could’ve been avoided but the owners didn’t do their homework and were not providing this pet/species their needs and then we run into health issues + veterinary intervention. I encourage annual vet exams at least for any species and find yourself a good, local vet that can help you be your best pet parent for your baby!
@conejovet

Can you take cats seriously? 
Neither can I 😹
Believe it or not, this is a common theme for me when I vaccinate cats. Most of my feline patients are shy, variably awkward, and just want to hide. I use this to my advantage and let them “hide” while I inject. Most cats also tolerate the actual needle injection quite well bc they’re so distracted simply being out of their home and in an exam room. This kitto was sweet, accepting & tolerant of our visit and appointments like this always make me smile 😸. 
@conejovet

You squeamish❓
Viewer discretion if sharp objects + eyeballs isn’t for you 👨🏻‍⚕️💁🏻‍♂️.
Eyelid tumors are typically benign tissue types however even benign tumors can become concerning if: 1. They protrude inward and contact the cornea, potentially damaging it with regular blinking 2. Their size or shape distorts healthy lid conformation and/or blinking 3. They grow too big, greater than 1/3rd the span of an upper or lower lid, because if it continues to grow and potentially eventually affect corneal health or blinking they’re much more complicated to remove when they’re occupying 1/3rd or more of eyelid width. 
Henry’s lid mass was not causing problems at this time but because of it’s increasing size and close proximity to a tear duct & tear gland I wanted to excise it (aka remove it) before it has a chance to become a more complicated surgery. Luckily surgery went well, Henry’s dental went well (only 2 incisors extracted) and his recovery was smooth. 
For fellow vets & nerds: I used hydromorphone 0.1 mg/kg premed and induced with midazolam 0.25 mg/kg followed by ketamine 5 mg/kg IV. I’ve used alfaxan & propofol for geriatric patients but I find that if their metabolic health is fine, heart health is normal to mild valvular disease, I like ketamine better for consistent gas/iso anesthesia %/levels and favorable blood pressure & heart rate. I use the exact same protocol in most young & middle aged dogs too (assuming they’re otherwise in good health). 
Suture: 4-0 Vicryl (braided, absorbable) Situational Pros: suture tags are soft & gentle on cornea, low memory, nice handling; Cons: Prone to harboring bacteria, leading to infection (although I’ve never had this happen after dozens of lid masses closed this way 🤞).
“Figure-8” closure (basically an upside-down cruciate). 
@conejovet

It is SO important to understand the difference between “good” and “bad” content regarding chimpanzees (primates) on social media. 
The difference can either lead to killing wild chimps and abducting baby chimps for the illegal pet trade (fueled by ‘bad’ content) or it can lead to chimp conservation thru awareness (promoted by ‘good’ content). 
Yes, YOU, can make a difference by being a little considerate about what you post, share, like, engage with because, good or bad, social media engagement DOES affect our wildlife. 
Big “thank you” to all of you that understand this and use social media with our wildlife in mind 🌍🙏

Repost from @janegoodallinst

We all like to ❤ chimpanzees, but did you know that some social content of chimpanzees that you “like” can be harmful? node.text:
Do you know why we close the gums over extracted teeth❓
Dental extractions are very common in small animal veterinary medicine and when a tooth is diseased beyond repair they’re extracted. Sometimes more intricate surgical options are warranted with a species or tooth (i.e. endodontics, sealants, etc) but these are rarely performed outside of board certified dental specialists. Did you know dogs & cats living at home get by just fine with little to no teeth!?
Anyhow, we close the gingiva (aka gums) to prevent food particles and debri from entering the alveolar space (aka the pocket(s) where the extracted tooth’s root(s) previously occupied) bc that potential space + rotting food can lead to infection. Suturing the gingiva from the buccal (outer side) & lingual (inner side) pulls them over the alveolar spaces & blocks debri from entering. That space fills with blood clots and scar tissue, leaving a healthy mouth. 
Btw following the tooth extraction, but prior to suturing, I also use a dental drill to smooth out the sharp edges of the alveolar rim to reduce pain on chewing & healing complications, and to help appose both sides of the gums to close effectively. 
Dental disease affects 75+% of dogs & cats by just 2 years of age! If YOU have concerns about your pet’s dental health plz contact your local vet. Most people don’t realize their pet has dental disease to begin with and that’s another reason I highly encourage annual vet exams so we can catch these things!
